05409nam a2200757Ia 9781501733611DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017336117 a10.7591/97815017336112doi  a(DE-B1597)506985  a(OCoLC)1052905377  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aTEC0590002bisacsh04a610.7205493qOCoLC223/eng/202311201 aSariola, Salla, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aResearch as Development :bBiomedical Research, Ethics, and Collaboration in Sri Lanka /cRobert Simpson, Salla Sariola. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (222 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. International Collaborative Research in Biomedicine: A Form of Development? -- t2. Collaboration in Context -- t3. The Joint Pain Trial -- t4. The Paraquat Poisoning Trial -- t5. Localizing Ethics -- t6. Negotiating Collaborative Research -- t7. Precarious Ethics -- t8. Strategic Ethics -- t9. Research as Development: Unintended Consequences -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Research as Development, Salla Sariola and Bob Simpson show how international collaboration operates in a setting that is typically portrayed as "resource-poor" and "scientifically lagging." Based on their long-term fieldwork in Sri Lanka, Sariola and Simpson bring into clear ethnographic focus the ways international scientific collaborations feature prominently in the pursuit of global health in which research operates "as" development and not merely "for" it. The authors follow the design, inception, and practice of two clinical trials: one a global health charity funded trial and the other a pharmaceutical industry-sponsored trial. Research as Development situates these two trials within their historical, political and cultural contexts and thus counters the idea that local actors are merely passive recipients of new technical and scientific rationalities. While social studies of clinical trials are beginning to be an established niche in academic writing, Research as Development helps fill important gaps in the literature through its examination of clinical research situated in cultures in low-income settings. Research as Development is noteworthy for the way it highlights the critical and creative role that local researchers play in establishing international collaborations and making them work into locally viable forms. The volume shows how these clinical and research interactions bring about changes in culture, technologies and expertise in Sri Lanka, contexts that have not previously been written about in any detail.  afunded by NEH CARES grant  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 4aHistory Of Technology. 7aTechnology & Engineering / Biomedical.2bisacsh  aglobal health, clinical trials, clinical research, international scientific collaborations, development.1 aSimpson, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut2 aNEH CARES grantefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Engineering, Computer Sciences 2019 Englishz978311061015408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Engineering, Computer Sciences 2019